  "prompt": "Why do we multiply vectors?",
  "response": "Vectors can be multiplied in different ways for different purposes:\n\n1. Dot Product (Scalar Product):\n- Gives a scalar (single number)\n- Measures vector alignment/angle\n- Useful in physics for calculating work and projections\n- Formula: A \u00b7 B = |A| |B| cos(\u03b8)\n\n2. Cross Product (Vector Product):\n- Produces a new vector perpendicular to both original vectors\n- Used in calculating torque, angular momentum\n- Determines area of parallelogram\n- Only defined for 3D vectors\n- Formula: A \u00d7 B = |A| |B| sin(\u03b8) n\n\n3. Scalar Multiplication:\n- Scales vector's magnitude\n- Changes vector's length without changing direction\n- Formula: k * A = (kA1, kA2, kA3)\n\n4. Matrix Multiplication:\n- Transforms vectors\n- Used in linear transformations, rotations\n- Important in computer graphics and physics simulations\n\nEach multiplication method serves different mathematical and physical purposes, helping to describe relationships, transformations, and interactions between vectors.",
